body:
> ... a user installs and starts tor, then ./bitcoind -onlynet=onion ...

For 1. to fail, then tor is not listening on `127.0.0.1:9051` which it does by default. So, maybe the user did not install and start tor or did so, but fiddled with its config and changed the listening address.

Anyway, maybe this change makes sense:

```diff
--- i/src/torcontrol.cpp
+++ w/src/torcontrol.cpp
@@ -612,13 +612,26 @@ void TorController::disconnected_cb(TorControlConnection& _conn)
     if (service.IsValid())
         RemoveLocal(service);
     service = CService();
     if (!reconnect)
         return;

-    LogPrint(BCLog::TOR, "Not connected to Tor control port %s, trying to reconnect\n", m_tor_control_
+    const auto onlynets = gArgs.GetArgs("-onlynet");
+    if (gArgs.IsArgSet("-onlynet") &&
+        std::any_of(onlynets.begin(), onlynets.end(), [](const auto& n) {
+            return ParseNetwork(n) == NET_ONION;
+        })) {
+        LogPrintf("Not connected to Tor control port %s, trying to reconnect. "
+                  "Use -listenonion=0 to disable the tor control thread.\n",
+                  m_tor_control_center);
+    } else {
+        LogPrint(BCLog::TOR,
+                 "Not connected to Tor control port %s, trying to reconnect. "
+                 "Use -listenonion=0 to disable the tor control thread.\n",
+                 m_tor_control_center);
+    }

     // Single-shot timer for reconnect. Use exponential backoff.
```

Keep it in the debug log only if `-onlynet=onion` is not given, because for users that did not install tor and do not care about tor and just run `bitcoind` this would be just noise.

